I   say   this a   lot   but it  keeps being   true: Every bad thing that a=
 public company does, and every bad thing that happens to a public company,=
 is also securities fraud.
The general form of this is something bad happens and the company does not =
immediately disclose it, or has not adequately warned shareholders of the r=
isk of it happening, or both. Later, when the bad news comes out, the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s stock drops. Shareholders who bought the stock before the news=
 came out sue, saying that they were deceived about the bad thing and lost =
money. The US Securities and Exchange Commission also takes an interest in =
fraud and might bring an enforcement action.
Take computer hacking, for instance.=C2=A0If a company gets hacked, that is=
 bad: The hack might disrupt its business, it might have to pay a ransom to=
 unlock its files, its customers might stop trusting it, it might get in tr=
ouble with regulators for losing customer data, etc. If a company gets hack=
ed and does not immediately disclose it, and then later discloses it and th=
e stock drops,   it will get sued for securities fraud. (Even if it does im=
mediately disclose it, it might get sued for not previously=C2=A0warning sh=
areholders about the risk of being hacked, or   for saying things like =E2=
=80=9Cwe use strong passwords=E2=80=9D if, in fact, it did not.)
Actually hacking is a special case, because getting hacked is=C2=A0so=C2=A0=
=C2=A0securities fraud that the SEC recently  wrote new rules about hacking=
 disclosure. These rules, which go into effect next month,=C2=A0require pub=
lic companies to disclose =E2=80=9Cany cybersecurity incident they determin=
e to be material=E2=80=9D=C2=A0within four days after they decide that it i=
s material.=C2=A0
One corollary of =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and this is the farthest possible thing from legal advice but h=
ere we are =E2=80=94=C2=A0one corollary of this is that, if you=C2=A0do=C2=
=A0a bad thing to a public company, once you have finished doing the bad th=
ing, there is a fascinating window in which:
=09You know about the bad thing, because you did it.=09The company knows ab=
out the bad thing, because it experienced it, and/or because you sent it=C2=
=A0an email like =E2=80=9Cnyah nyah I just hacked your computers.=E2=80=9D=
=09The public does=C2=A0not=C2=A0know about the bad thing, because the comp=
any has not yet disclosed it.

By the theory of =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0the=
 company is committing securities fraud during this window. (Particularly i=
f the bad thing was a hack and the window has been more than four days.)=C2=
=A0And you know it. How can you take advantage?
One thing that you could do is short the company=E2=80=99s stock, hoping to=
 profit when the bad thing is disclosed. This is a well-established approac=
h, but has the problem of being illegal. It is (probably) insider trading: =
You have material nonpublic information about the company, and are trading =
on it.
  [1]
=C2=A0You might not care: If you did an illegal=C2=A0bad thing to the compa=
ny (like hacking), also doing insider trading might not bother you. Still i=
t adds some risk. My   Fifth Law of Insider Trading is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=
=99t insider trade by planting bombs at a company and buying put options on=
 its stock.=E2=80=9D
Another thing you could do is sue the company for securities fraud, but tha=
t takes a lot of time and effort. Also you won=E2=80=99t get that much mone=
y for it unless you owned a lot of the company=E2=80=99s stock, and presuma=
bly you didn=E2=80=99t. (If you did, why did you do the bad thing to the co=
mpany?)
A third thing you could do is file a whistleblower complaint with the US Se=
curities and Exchange Commission saying =E2=80=9Chey FYI this company is do=
ing securities fraud.=E2=80=9D And then maybe the SEC will investigate and =
agree and fine the company a pile of money and give you a cut of the money =
as a whistleblower reward. The SEC does the work for you and just hands you=
 the money at the end. Efficient!
Anyway here is maybe  the most Money Stuff story I=E2=80=99ve ever written =
about:

The ALPHV/BlackCat ransomware operation has taken extortion to a new level =
by filing a U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission complaint against one o=
f their alleged victims for not complying with the four-day rule to disclos=
e a cyberattack.
Earlier today, the threat actor listed the software company MeridianLink on=
 their data leak with a threat that they would leak allegedly stolen data u=
nless a ransom is paid in 24 hours.

LOVE IT. Apparently AlphV hacked into MeridianLink=E2=80=99s computers on N=
ov. 7;  DataBreaches.net says that =E2=80=9Cthey did not encrypt any files,=
 but did exfiltrate files.=E2=80=9D And then they asked MeridianLink for a =
ransom payment, threatening to release the information they had obtained un=
less they got paid. And then apparently MeridianLink did not pay them=C2=A0=
or=C2=A0publicly disclose the hack, so AlphV went to  the SEC website and f=
illed out a tip form. Their submission to the SEC included a bit of legal a=
nalysis:
It has come to our attention that MeridianLink, in light of a significant b=
reach compromising customer data and operational information, has failed to=
 file the requisite disclosure under Item 1.05 of Form 8-K within the stipu=
lated four business days, as mandated by the new SEC rules.
Do you think =E2=80=A6=C2=A0do you think the ransomware collective=E2=80=99=
s lawyers wrote that? Do you think they hired a former SEC enforcement lawy=
er to do their whistleblower submissions? Did they have an executive meetin=
g where some ambitious young hacker was like =E2=80=9Clook ransom is great =
but I think we have a real opportunity to expand into the SEC whistleblowin=
g space, it=E2=80=99s pretty simple to add to our current product so we won=
=E2=80=99t need a ton of engineering resources but to maximize returns we r=
eally need to hire someone familiar with the SEC=E2=80=9D? If you work at t=
he SEC and are considering a private-sector job offer from a ransomware col=
lective please, please, please email me about it.
There are problems with their submission, of course:
=09The Item 1.05 disclosure rules don=E2=80=99t go into effect until next m=
onth, though those rules largely codify prior SEC guidance=C2=A0and the SEC=
 probably already thinks that not promptly disclosing a hack is securities =
fraud.=09MeridianLink  told DataBreaches that =E2=80=9Cbased on our investi=
gation to date, we have identified no evidence of unauthorized access to ou=
r production platforms, and the incident has caused minimal business interr=
uption.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s entirely possible that this hack was=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0material, which is why MeridianLink neither disclosed it nor paid up.=
=C2=A0=09Look come on they are obviously not getting a whistleblower award =
even if they are right! They did the hack! This is not really a=C2=A0play f=
or money, this is just some combination of (1) attention-seeking prank (it =
worked!) and (2) another way to annoy MeridianLink, another threat, a way=
=C2=A0to extort this victim and future victims into paying up promptly.

Do you think they read Money Stuff? I=C2=A0feel like I have done a lot to p=
opularize the idea that everything is securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0not a=
s much as the SEC, but a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it is nice to see how far t=
he idea has traveled.

