   =20
      Ad valorem
   =20
 =20

If Rivian Automotive Inc. bought some land in Georgia and built a big facto=
ry there, it would have to pay Georgia property taxes on the factory. If, i=
nstead, the government of the state of Georgia bought the land and built th=
e factory there, and Rivian just=C2=A0rented=C2=A0it from the state, it wou=
ld not have to pay the taxes.
  [2]
=C2=A0If Georgia really really wants Rivian to build a factory in Georgia, =
it might want=C2=A0to give Rivian that=C2=A0tax reduction, as sort of a wel=
come gift.
But one doesn=E2=80=99t want the gift to be too lavish. The gift is =E2=80=
=9Cyou don=E2=80=99t have to pay the full property tax rate on your factory=
,=E2=80=9D not =E2=80=9Cwe will literally buy the land and build the factor=
y for you.=E2=80=9D Rivian still has to build the factory! And the specific=
 series of incantations that you utter, in Georgia, to make this all work i=
s
  [3]
:
=09Georgia, or more accurately a Georgia government entity called the JDA,
  [4]
 agrees to issue=C2=A0up to $15 billion of municipal bonds, from time to ti=
me, to pay for the land and construction.=09Rivian agrees to buy the bonds =
whenever they are issued.=09Rivian also agrees to rent the land and factory=
 from the JDA.=09Whenever Rivian needs to spend a slug of money on the fact=
ory, it sends the JDA a notice saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re spending $100 =
million=E2=80=9D or whatever, and then the JDA sends back a notice saying =
=E2=80=9Cgreat we=E2=80=99re selling you $100 million of bonds.=E2=80=9D
  [5]

=09And then Rivian just spends the $100 million, but everyone agrees that i=
n some entirely abstract sense what happened is that Rivian paid $100 milli=
on to the JDA to buy bonds, and the JDA issued the bonds to Rivian, and the=
 JDA got the money, and the JDA gave the money to Rivian, and Rivian spent =
it. No actual money changes hands between Rivian and the JDA; they all just=
 agree to look at Rivian=E2=80=99s spending in a peculiar way.
  [6]

=09Of course then the =E2=80=9Cbonds=E2=80=9D are =E2=80=9Coutstanding,=E2=
=80=9D and the JDA =E2=80=9Cowes=E2=80=9D Rivian the =E2=80=9C$100 million=
=E2=80=9D plus =E2=80=9Cinterest,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but this too is completely =
abstract, and the way it works is, notionally,=C2=A0that Rivian pays the JD=
A the $100 million plus interest as =E2=80=9Crent=E2=80=9D for the factory,=
 and the JDA pays that back to Rivian as =E2=80=9Cprincipal and interest=E2=
=80=9D on the bonds. Again, no money changes hands either way; this is just=
 a further peculiar way to look at Rivian=E2=80=99s spending to make the bo=
oks balance.
  [7]

=09At the end of the rental term (in December 2047) Rivian gets to buy the =
land and factory for $100.
  [8]



The result is that, for the term of the agreement, the JDA=C2=A0technically=
=C2=A0owns the factory, but Rivian actually pays to build it. But since it =
doesn=E2=80=99t own it, it doesn=E2=80=99t pay taxes. (It does make negotia=
ted=C2=A0payments in lieu of taxes, but at a lower rate.)
Fun! Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Amanda Albright reports:

Electric-vehicle maker Rivian Automotive Inc. released what would usually b=
e a startling announcement for the municipal-finance market: A potential $1=
5 billion bond for a Georgia campus, that would in theory be the largest ev=
er muni sale and nearly the size of the company=E2=80=99s market cap.
Except, the bonds aren=E2=80=99t real.
The debt is structured as what=E2=80=99s known as =E2=80=9Cphantom bonds=E2=
=80=9D that are used by companies to get a property tax break in Georgia, a=
nd involve no real financial or accounting impact for the company involved,=
 according to a report by law firm Smith, Gambrell & Russell LLP. In Rivian=
=E2=80=99s case, it=E2=80=99s a workaround because the state doesn=E2=80=99=
t have legislation allowing for companies to get abatements that provide su=
ch relief.
The massive =E2=80=94 yet essentially fictitious =E2=80=94 sale is necessar=
y as part of what=E2=80=99s one of the largest economic development project=
s in Georgia=E2=80=99s history. It=E2=80=99s also indicative of the fierce =
arms-race states embark on to land massive manufacturing deals that promise=
 high-paying jobs and an economic boon. The company says it will create 7,5=
00 jobs and that once up and running, the facility will eventually produce =
as much as 400,000 vehicles per year. ...
=E2=80=9CThe whole concept is set up for a break on the ad-valorem taxes,=
=E2=80=9D John Shakarjian, Rivian=E2=80=99s associate general counsel for r=
eal estate and construction, said in an interview. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s=
 no cash changing hands, there=E2=80=99s no cash being generated, there=E2=
=80=99s no movement of money.=E2=80=9D
Shakarjian said Georgia=E2=80=99s system for economic development projects =
was unusual among US states and even among countries abroad. He noted it=E2=
=80=99s common for companies in Georgia to use the phantom-bond structure.

Love it. You could imagine the government of Georgia just saying =E2=80=9Cy=
ou know what, never mind all this,=C2=A0you=C2=A0just build the factory and=
 we=E2=80=99ll waive your taxes for a bit.=E2=80=9D But apparently that=E2=
=80=99s not allowed =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe state doesn=E2=80=99t have =
legislation allowing for companies to get abatements=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0so it does this instead. Which comes to the same place, but=C2=A0provide=
s much more entertainment for lawyers, and for me.

