   =20
      Elsewhere in whistleblower incentives
   =20
 =20

More generally. Let=E2=80=99s say you find something bad at a public compan=
y that the rest of the market does not know about. (Let=E2=80=99s say you d=
idn=E2=80=99t do the bad thing yourself.) Let=E2=80=99s say that you know w=
ith certainty that, when you disclose your bad news, the company=E2=80=99s =
value will decline by 20%. It=E2=80=99s a company with a $1 billion market =
capitalization, and once the market knows about your news it will be worth =
$800 million. What should you do?
You could sell the stock short. Say you short $100 million of stock, tying =
up roughly $100 million of your balance sheet and risk exposure. You publis=
h your news, the market reacts, your position declines to $80 million, you =
cover, you have made $20 million. That is probably too optimistic; it=E2=80=
=99s not easy to short 10% of a company=E2=80=99s stock, and you=E2=80=99ll=
 probably pay a lot in stock borrow costs.
  [9]

Or you could file an SEC whistleblower complaint. How much is that worth to=
 you? Well, the bull case is something like:
=09The bad thing cost shareholders $200 million.=09The SEC will make the co=
mpany pay=C2=A0the $200 million of damages as a penalty (and give some of i=
t to the aggrieved shareholders).
  [10]

=09The SEC will give you 30% of the damages, or $60 million.

You have made three times as much money, and you=C2=A0haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0=
tied up $100 million of balance sheet, or taken any risk:
  [11]
If you turn out to be completely wrong about the bad news or the market rea=
ction, you don=E2=80=99t lose any money, whereas if=C2=A0you had shorted yo=
u would have.
Now, that math is also way too optimistic: The SEC whistleblower program mo=
ves a lot more slowly than the market, and there is no guarantee that the S=
EC will investigate, that they will bring a case, that they will win (or se=
ttle), that they will ask for (or get) anything like those maximum damages,=
 that they will judge you to be a worthy whistleblower, or that they will g=
ive you 30% even if they do. (=E2=80=9CWhistleblower awards can range from =
10 to 30 percent of the money collected when the monetary sanctions exceed =
$1 million,=E2=80=9D  says the SEC.)
Still, if you discount that math by 90% for its various uncertainties, your=
 expected profit on this trade is=C2=A0$6 million, with no capital=C2=A0at =
risk. I=E2=80=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0better, in the abstract, than =
shorting the stock, but it=E2=80=99s an interesting alternative.
Also, of course, why not both? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Austin Weinstein repor=
ts:

Alongside their public reports, short sellers are quietly sharing their res=
earch about sketchy accounting and other misdeeds with the US Securities an=
d Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s whistleblower office in hopes of making som=
e extra money.
The practice is widespread, with big-name short sellers Nate Anderson, Kyle=
 Bass and Carson Block among the tipsters. If the SEC investigates and levi=
es a fine, a short seller can collect up to 30% of the proceeds. That=E2=80=
=99s on top of any profit they might make by betting on the stock=E2=80=99s=
 decline. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThe center of gravity in this program is shifting to short sellers=
,=E2=80=9D said Alexander Platt, a University of Kansas law professor who h=
as written about the trend. =E2=80=9CI think the taxpayers should know when=
 $14 million of our money goes to Carson Block.=E2=80=9D

Well but who do you think whistleblower money is going to, if it=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0not=C2=A0going to Carson Block? Often it is going to people who worke=
d at companies, did fraud, and then realized that they could make more mone=
y by blowing the whistle on the fraud than by continuing to do it. Whistleb=
lower awards are not a reward for upstanding good citizenship; they are a r=
eward for exposing fraud, and you=E2=80=99re not always going to like the p=
eople who know about the frauds.
And of course, over time, a lucrative whistleblower program is going to be=
=C2=A0professionalized:=C2=A0The =E2=80=9Ccenter of gravity=E2=80=9D is goi=
ng to shift from amateur whistleblowers (people who happened to work on a f=
raud once) to professionals (people whose whole job is finding frauds and p=
rofiting from them).
  [12]

I suppose that if you are the SEC, the question might be: How much securiti=
es fraud is optimal to catch and punish? You could imagine answers like:
=09100%. Fraud is bad and you have to punish it every time.=0950%. Catch th=
e biggest frauds, the most egregious frauds, and create a lot of deterrence=
 so that other companies don=E2=80=99t do fraud. But in a world of finite r=
esources it is not really possible to catch every fraud, and the SEC has th=
ings to do other than catching public-company accounting fraud.=C2=A0=09110=
%. Anyone who even gets close to the line has to pay a big fine, and even i=
f they didn=E2=80=99t do anything=C2=A0really=C2=A0wrong it=E2=80=99s okay =
because it creates deterrence and brings in money for the government (and t=
o pay whistleblowers).

You could imagine the SEC, when it created the whistleblower program, think=
ing =E2=80=9Cwe only catch 30% of fraud and it would be optimal to shift th=
at up to like 40%, surely paying some money to whistleblowers will help wit=
h that.=E2=80=9D But the result is that it now advertises risk-free unlimit=
ed money to short sellers, and they will give it as much fraud as it can ha=
ndle, maybe more.

